**Reduce Costs, Improve Quality of Living**

How One G7 Mission is Transforming &nbsp;Its New York Property Portfolio

\
\

*A 50-unit housing portfolio \
A $23M annual budget\
$50M+ in projected savings after Phase 1*

\
\

Spring 2026****

# **Executive Summary**

\

A G7 nation’s diplomatic presence in New York City spans two missions, approximately 50 staff housing units, three official residences, and one chancery. The portfolio has grown organically over decades — a patchwork of owned units in aging buildings and leased apartments at escalating rents, managed by a small but dedicated seven-person property team operating under a budget of approximately $23 million per year.

The mission’s leadership recognized that the portfolio no longer fully aligns with the organization’s needs: units are the wrong size for incoming staff, owned assets are aging with major upcoming capital needs, rent ceilings imposed by headquarters are increasingly mismatched with the New York market, while the organization is exposed to challenging landlord practices and inflexibility common in the city.

Working with Aabo Advisory at the Erin Boisson Aries Team at Douglas Elliman, the mission undertook a comprehensive phased portfolio transformation — from diagnostic review through execution — that so far has resulted in 10 completed transactions, 9 leases identified for exit, and projected net savings exceeding $50 million over a 30-year horizon - on the first phase alone.

This case study documents the process, the framework, and the results for other organizations to take note, find inspiration and pursue similar outcomes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

\

*The goal was straightforward: better housing, lower costs. \
The method was disciplined. The results exceeded expectations.*

# **1. The Starting Position**

\

## **Portfolio Snapshot**

