## **Tips From the Field**

Several practical lessons emerged during execution that are transferable to any mission undertaking a similar effort:

- **Batch your searches.** Rather than sourcing one property at a time, identify 15–25 candidates that meet criteria, then schedule visits in concentrated blocks. This is dramatically more efficient and gives you comparative data.
- **Brief your building contacts early.** New development sales teams move fast. Establishing a relationship before you are ready to offer gives you early access to inventory and pricing flexibility.
- **Prepare HQ for velocity.** New York real estate moves on days, not months. If headquarters approval takes six weeks, good properties will be gone. Pre-negotiate approval thresholds and delegated authority before you begin searching.
- **Use a standardized walkthrough.** Every property visit should follow a consistent inspection protocol with documented punch lists. This protects the mission at closing and creates an institutional record.
- **Align closings with the fiscal calendar.** Government budget cycles are not negotiable. Work backward from your fiscal year-end to ensure closing timelines are realistic, and communicate this to sellers and developers from the outset.
- **Negotiate as a portfolio buyer.** When purchasing multiple units in the same building or development, you have leverage. Use it. Volume pricing, priority unit selection, and customization concessions are all achievable.

